he'll need a full
hypercoagulable workup,

253
00:11:10,353 --> 00:11:14,906
including factor V Leiden,
protein C, and S levels.

254
00:11:14,958 --> 00:11:17,458
If all goes well, we'll
get you out of here

255
00:11:17,544 --> 00:11:19,655
- in a couple of hours.
- No. We'll keep him overnight,

256
00:11:19,679 --> 00:11:22,146
- just for observation, hmm?
- We're gonna do

257
00:11:22,215 --> 00:11:24,615
everything we can to get
you back on that mound.

258
00:11:24,684 --> 00:11:25,817
All right. Thanks, man.

259
00:11:25,885 --> 00:11:27,451
I mean, Dr...

260
00:11:27,521 --> 00:11:29,453
Devon.

261
00:11:29,523 --> 00:11:32,657
- Just... you know what, just call me Devon.
- Devon.

262
00:11:32,726 --> 00:11:34,759
All right. Thanks.

263
00:11:38,698 --> 00:11:41,566
So why do they call
him "Dr. Smooth"?

264
00:11:41,634 --> 00:11:43,512
Massero hates
conflict, he hates drama

265
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:45,748
and he really hates
delivering bad news to patients

266
00:11:45,772 --> 00:11:47,517
who pay him a lot of
money not to hear it,

267
00:11:47,541 --> 00:11:50,775
so he outsources the
tough love to grunts like us.

268
00:11:50,844 --> 00:11:54,028
Which makes me think
Bobby has a big problem.

269
00:11:56,199 --> 00:11:58,433
- Hey.
- Hey.

270
00:11:58,502 --> 00:11:59,667
So, Noni?

271
00:11:59,736 --> 00:12:01,936
We've got a DVT consult on Six.

272
00:12:02,005 --> 00:12:03,649
He might need
surgical management.

273
00:12:03,673 --> 00:12:05,873
- Can you see him?
- Yeah, I'll check my schedule.

274
00:12:05,908 --> 00:12:08,909
Fair to say you're over Nic.

275
00:12:13,567 --> 00:12:15,967
Our clinical volume
is growing so fast,

276
00:12:16,036 --> 00:12:18,619
we're having difficulty moving
them through the system,

277
00:12:18,688 --> 00:12:20,399
which is probably what
happened to Mrs. Shea.

278
00:12:20,423 --> 00:12:22,656
Okay, and Darryl Phillips?

279
00:12:22,743 --> 00:12:25,677
I need someone to
perform his biopsy today.

280
00:12:25,745 --> 00:12:29,414
Excuse me. Uh, regarding
Mr. Phillips's biopsy.

281
00:12:29,482 --> 00:12:30,815
Are you following Mr. Phillips?

282
00:12:30,867 --> 00:12:32,050
He is not.

283
00:12:32,119 --> 00:12:33,762
I am now. I was
asked to speak with him

284
00:12:33,786 --> 00:12:36,554
after he had second
thoughts about his treatment.

285
00:12:36,623 --> 00:12:38,101
As you know, his
prognosis is terminal.

286
00:12:38,125 --> 00:12:40,691
And how would you know
that for sure without the biopsy?

287
00:12:40,761 --> 00:12:42,371
CT scan and tumor
markers are suggestive

288
00:12:42,395 --> 00:12:44,695
of small-cell lung cancer
with mets to the liver,

289
00:12:44,765 --> 00:12:45,765
stage IV.

290
00:12:47,067 --> 00:12:49,016
His prognosis is extremely poor.

291
00:12:49,085 --> 00:12:50,668
Yes,

292
00:12:50,737 --> 00:12:52,865
and with what little
time he has left, he'd like

293
00:12:52,889 --> 00:12:54,767
to get his affairs in order
and be at home with his wife.

294
00:12:54,791 --> 00:12:57,074
Well, a biopsy helps
us definitively tailor

295
00:12:57,144 --> 00:12:59,243
his treatment,
especially in the event

296
00:12:59,312 --> 00:13:01,257
that it's not
small-cell lung cancer.

297
00:13:01,281 --> 00:13:04,515
Mr. Phillips doesn't want the
biopsy, since he doesn't want

298
00:13:04,568 --> 00:13:06,796
a treatment that's unlikely
to change his outcome.

299
00:13:06,820 --> 00:13:07,919
Unlikely?

300
00:13:07,987 --> 00:13:10,521
We punt on unlikely
outcomes now?

301
00:13:10,589 --> 00:13:12,423
We do not.

302
00:13:12,492 --> 00:13:14,108
Even if it is small-cell,

303
00:13:14,177 --> 00:13:16,460
chemoradiation is still
an option worth exploring.

304
00:13:16,529 --> 00:13:19,714
I will speak to the patient,
make sure he understands

305
00:13:19,783 --> 00:13:22,550
- the upside of chemo one more time.
- O-Okay,

306
00:13:22,636 --> 00:13:24,363
so i-in the future, just so I'm
clear, in these tumor board

307
00:13:24,387 --> 00:13:26,065
meetings, we don't factor
in what the patient wants?

308
00:13:26,089 --> 00:13:27,699
I'm just asking,
so I don't waste

309
00:13:27,723 --> 00:13:29,140
any more of your valuable time.

310
00:13:29,209 --> 00:13:30,558
That's enough, Conrad.

311
00:13:30,627 --> 00:13:32,587
All right, I need
someone to perform

312
00:13:32,646 --> 00:13:34,045
Mr. Phillips's biopsy today.

313
00:13:34,114 --> 00:13:35,363
Where is Vincent?

314
00:13:35,432 --> 00:13:38,716
I'm free this afternoon.

315
00:13:38,768 --> 00:13:40,496
- I can do it.
- Thank you, Jude.

316
00:13:40,520 --> 00:13:42,737
But I think we should
wait for Dr. Vincent.

317
00:13:42,823 --> 00:13:45,272
Okay, thank you, everyone.

318
00:13:45,358 --> 00:13:47,424
Conrad.

319
00:13:54,801 --> 00:13:56,812
I want you there when
I talk to Mr. Phillips,

320
00:13:56,836 --> 00:13:58,519
so there's no more confusion.

321
00:14:01,875 --> 00:14:03,440
What was that?

322
00:14:03,510 --> 00:14:05,154
The patient doesn't
want the biopsy.

323
00:14:05,178 --> 00:14:06,477
Well, I didn't argue for one.

324
00:14:06,546 --> 00:14:08,024
I just volunteered
to do the procedure.

325
00:14:08,048 --> 00:14:10,092
Darryl Phillips just
wants to go home and die,

326
00:14:10,116 --> 00:14:12,210
but there's no money in
it for Chastain if he leaves

327
00:14:12,234 --> 00:14:14,835
- without more treatment.
- Okay, calm down.

328
00:14:14,904 --> 00:14:16,638
What is this?

329
00:14:16,706 --> 00:14:18,289
Is this about me and Nic?

330
00:14:18,358 --> 00:14:20,825
This has nothing to
do with you and Nic,

331
00:14:20,894 --> 00:14:22,571
and everything to
do with Darryl Phillips,

332
00:14:22,595 --> 00:14:23,862
whose dying wish is to go home.

333
00:14:23,930 --> 00:14:25,930
Okay, don't you forget:

334
00:14:25,999 --> 00:14:28,766
I'm the attending, and
you're the resident, brother.

335
00:14:28,835 --> 00:14:31,870
So, technically, you outrank me,
but that doesn't change the fact

336
00:14:31,938 --> 00:14:33,716
that you don't know
what you're talking about.

337
00:14:33,740 --> 00:14:36,274
You and I aren't in the
military anymore, brother.

338
00:14:36,343 --> 00:14:40,060
I don't even need to salute you.

339
00:14:46,836 --> 00:14:49,337
You're here to tell me
you saved my job today

340
00:14:49,405 --> 00:14:51,538
at the board meeting.

341
00:14:51,607 --> 00:14:53,224
Word gets around fast.

342
00:14:53,293 --> 00:14:55,826
Oh, it does, when you're
the one spreading it.

343
00:14:56,963 --> 00:14:58,241
They were looking
for a scapegoat,

344
00:14:58,265 --> 00:14:59,681
I made sure it wasn't you.

345
00:14:59,766 --> 00:15:03,701
That should make you
the opposite of angry.

346
00:15:03,770 --> 00:15:05,147
No, I'm here to tell
you we'll be able

347
00:15:05,171 --> 00:15:06,682
to work together
again as partners.

348
00:15:06,706 --> 00:15:10,041
I think we had some
nice momentum going.

349
00:15:10,109 --> 00:15:12,326
I'm not ready.

350
00:15:12,412 --> 00:15:15,196
I'm sorry.

351
00:15:15,282 --> 00:15:18,215
I am not ready to work with you.

352
00:15:19,703 --> 00:15:22,169
You were right, what you
said at my M&M hearing.

353
00:15:23,790 --> 00:15:25,390
I wasn't ready.

354
00:15:25,458 --> 00:15:27,541
I want to be ready next time.

355
00:15:27,627 --> 00:15:30,662
Well, we won't put
you in a position

356
00:15:30,730 --> 00:15:31,862
to fail again.

357
00:15:31,932 --> 00:15:33,731
No, thanks.

358
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:35,533
I'll serve my penance studying,

359
00:15:35,601 --> 00:15:38,920
and doing prostatectomies
on the Titian.

360
00:15:38,988 --> 00:15:41,855
Well, y-yeah. You
need permission...

361
00:15:41,924 --> 00:15:45,243
I sought and received permission
from the residency board

362
00:15:45,312 --> 00:15:47,995
to work under Dr. Kays
for the next three months.

363
00:15:49,999 --> 00:15:51,815
Excuse me.

364
00:15:56,289 --> 00:15:58,089
What kind of research project?

365
00:15:58,158 --> 00:15:59,852
On your promising treatment
regimen at your clinic.

366
00:15:59,876 --> 00:16:01,954
A retrospective review
focused on outcomes

367
00:16:01,978 --> 00:16:03,745
and disease-free intervals.

368
00:16:03,813 --> 00:16:06,547
When it's published, it could
bring in even more patients,

369
00:16:06,633 --> 00:16:09,299
- and save lives.
- And you think you're the first resident

370
00:16:09,368 --> 00:16:11,835
to approach me about
writing a research paper?

371
00:16:11,888 --> 00:16:14,238
Of course not,
but they're not me.

372
00:16:14,307 --> 00:16:16,174
Hmm.

373
00:16:16,242 --> 00:16:18,176
Well, thank you,

374
00:16:18,244 --> 00:16:21,161
but a manuscript for
a prestigious journal

375
00:16:21,230 --> 00:16:23,631
is already in progress.

376
00:16:26,035 --> 00:16:27,367
Anything else?

377
00:16:27,437 --> 00:16:29,036
No.

378
00:16:29,104 --> 00:16:31,472
Appreciate your time.

379
00:16:37,864 --> 00:16:39,530
She definitely wasn't into it.

380
00:16:39,599 --> 00:16:41,560
Doctors don't mind multiple
papers published, as long

381
00:16:41,584 --> 00:16:44,013
as they're favorable. She just
doesn't want you poking around.

382
00:16:44,037 --> 00:16:45,947
Yeah, maybe it's time I
quit thinking like a doctor,

383
00:16:45,971 --> 00:16:47,971
and start thinking
like a journalist.

384
00:16:51,060 --> 00:16:55,012
Darryl, I know my aggressive
regimen can seem daunting,

385
00:16:55,081 --> 00:16:57,448
but cancer is a
relentless enemy,

386
00:16:57,517 --> 00:16:59,495
and you have to fight it
with extreme prejudice.

387
00:16:59,519 --> 00:17:01,397
You have to fight
it with fire and fury.

388
00:17:01,421 --> 00:17:03,421
You can't just give up.

389
00:17:03,490 --> 00:17:06,007
That's why people from all
over the world come to my clinics,

390
00:17:06,075 --> 00:17:08,542
because I never give up.

391
00:17:08,611 --> 00:17:12,079
Yes, the survival rate for
your prognosis is not great.

392
00:17:12,148 --> 00:17:13,447
Not great?

393
00:17:13,516 --> 00:17:15,649
- It's nil.
- You're wrong.

394
00:17:15,718 --> 00:17:18,752
There's always a chance
that you can be the outlier,

395
00:17:18,822 --> 00:17:21,471
someone who beat the odds.

396
00:17:21,541 --> 00:17:22,757
I told you, honey.

397
00:17:22,826 --> 00:17:25,893
But I need to know
my enemy to fight it.

398
00:17:25,962 --> 00:17:27,962
What do you think, Doc?

399
00:17:28,031 --> 00:17:30,564
Dr. Hawkins is an
incredible doctor,

400
00:17:30,633 --> 00:17:32,383
but he's an internist.

401
00:17:32,452 --> 00:17:34,602
He doesn't treat cancer.

402
00:17:34,671 --> 00:17:36,487
I'm your oncologist,

403
00:17:36,556 --> 00:17:39,123
and I know what I'm doing.

404
00:17:39,192 --> 00:17:41,125
Okay, I guess.

405
00:17:41,194 --> 00:17:42,777
Do the biopsy.

406
00:17:42,846 --> 00:17:44,912
Oh, okay.

407
00:17:44,981 --> 00:17:45,981
Yes.

408
00:17:46,048 --> 00:17:47,381
Thank you.

409
00:17:51,988 --> 00:17:54,154
I saw you pitch a two-hitter

410
00:17:54,223 --> 00:17:57,841
against Chicago
in 2014 and lose.

411
00:17:57,910 --> 00:17:59,676
Yeah, on a throwing error.

412
00:17:59,746 --> 00:18:01,724
- What are you testing for?
- Find out what's causing

413
00:18:01,748 --> 00:18:03,130
what's causing the clot.

414
00:18:03,199 --> 00:18:05,344
You've been through
Tommy John surgery.

415
00:18:05,368 --> 00:18:07,067
You can come back from this.

416
00:18:07,136 --> 00:18:08,035
All right, so after you fix it,

417
00:18:08,104 --> 00:18:09,753
when can I start throwing again?

418
00:18:09,822 --> 00:18:12,272
- That's up to your team doctor.
- And you,

419
00:18:12,342 --> 00:18:14,119
- but you can't come back too soon.
- Why?

420
00:18:14,143 --> 00:18:15,738
- What would happen if I did?
- Well, that depends.

421
00:18:15,762 --> 00:18:19,163
- It depends on the results of the test.
- Yeah.

422
00:18:19,232 --> 00:18:21,552
This conversation's not
really constructive right now.

423
00:18:21,601 --> 00:18:23,245
Bobby, I want you to meet
the chief executive officer

424
00:18:23,269 --> 00:18:25,147
of Chastain. She wanted
to come up and say hello,

425
00:18:25,171 --> 00:18:26,703
and, uh, see how you're doing.

426
00:18:26,773 --> 00:18:28,038
We've actually met before.

427
00:18:28,107 --> 00:18:30,187
You helped us raise
awareness and finances

428
00:18:30,243 --> 00:18:32,025
for our children's hospital.

429
00:18:32,112 --> 00:18:34,032
That's right. It's
good to see you.

430
00:18:34,063 --> 00:18:36,341
- Well, thank you, Doctor. I'll take it from here.
- Right.

431
00:18:36,365 --> 00:18:38,394
- And can I speak to you for a second?
- Absolutely.

432
00:18:38,418 --> 00:18:40,550
Thank you again for
choosing Chastain.

433
00:18:40,620 --> 00:18:42,019
Of course.

434
00:18:42,088 --> 00:18:45,572
And, uh, we'll be back
to check on you later.

435
00:18:45,658 --> 00:18:47,136
All right, man.

436
00:18:47,160 --> 00:18:48,804
Hey, is this a bad time?

437
00:18:48,828 --> 00:18:50,222
Yeah.

438
00:18:50,246 --> 00:18:51,178
All right, I'll come back.

439
00:18:51,247 --> 00:18:52,312
Hey, it's all right.

440
00:18:52,381 --> 00:18:53,748
Come on in.

441
00:18:53,833 --> 00:18:54,998
I can sign those for you.

442
00:18:55,067 --> 00:18:56,367
Oh, uh, not for me.

443
00:18:56,436 --> 00:18:57,696
Some of the kids
in the pediatric ward

444
00:18:57,720 --> 00:19:00,020
heard you were up here.

445
00:19:00,089 --> 00:19:01,789
That's great. Here.

446
00:19:01,858 --> 00:19:04,408
- I'm happy to help.
- Thank you.

447
00:19:04,477 --> 00:19:06,260
I can get some swag

448
00:19:06,346 --> 00:19:07,277
for the kids.

449
00:19:07,347 --> 00:19:08,796
Hats, jerseys.

450
00:19:08,864 --> 00:19:10,564
Aw, that's really sweet.

451
00:19:10,650 --> 00:19:13,901
Here. Let me get
your phone number.

452
00:19:13,987 --> 00:19:15,336
It's fine.

453
00:19:15,405 --> 00:19:17,755
Look, if you want, I can
just give you my number,

454
00:19:17,824 --> 00:19:19,001
- and you can contact me when...
- Oh, no, no, no.

455
00:19:19,025 --> 00:19:20,124
It's fine, sorry. Here,

456
00:19:20,193 --> 00:19:22,075
I'll just punch it in, here.

457
00:19:22,162 --> 00:19:24,028
There you go.

458
00:19:24,096 --> 00:19:25,679
Thanks again for these.

459
00:19:31,454 --> 00:19:33,420
Oh... this has peppers.

460
00:19:33,489 --> 00:19:36,574
I think it's yours.

461
00:19:36,626 --> 00:19:39,559
So how's it going with
that, um, that Pinetree story?

462
00:19:39,629 --> 00:19:41,028
Pinewick.

463
00:19:41,097 --> 00:19:42,891
I told you, there's not
enough evidence yet

464
00:19:42,915 --> 00:19:45,182
to link the toxic
landfill to the clusters.

465
00:19:45,251 --> 00:19:46,933
Right.

466
00:19:47,002 --> 00:19:49,198
Hey, uh, just curious... Were
any of the cancer patients

467
00:19:49,222 --> 00:19:51,789
you interviewed
treated by Dr. Hunter?

468
00:19:51,858 --> 00:19:54,291
Your Lane Hunter?

469
00:19:54,360 --> 00:19:55,492
Yeah.

470
00:19:55,561 --> 00:19:57,261
No. Why?

471
00:19:57,313 --> 00:20:00,247
Uh, just wondering. If
they'd been treated by her,

472
00:20:00,316 --> 00:20:01,844
maybe there'd be evidence
that could link their cancer

473
00:20:01,868 --> 00:20:03,467
with the landfill.

474
00:20:03,536 --> 00:20:06,586
Evidence I could help you get.

475
00:20:06,656 --> 00:20:09,406
That's nice of you.

476
00:20:09,459 --> 00:20:11,625
Just trying to be supportive.

477
00:20:11,694 --> 00:20:13,839
I suppose there could be
patients in the cluster study

478
00:20:13,863 --> 00:20:17,180
that I didn't interview who
were Lane Hunter's patients.

479
00:20:17,249 --> 00:20:18,882
I could try to find them.

480
00:20:18,951 --> 00:20:20,984
Why?

481
00:20:21,054 --> 00:20:23,454
Is there a story here?

482
00:20:23,506 --> 00:20:26,107
Maybe.

483
00:20:26,175 --> 00:20:27,441
For sure, there would be

484
00:20:27,510 --> 00:20:29,238
a conflict of interest
for the both of us,

485
00:20:29,262 --> 00:20:33,196
and the possibility of
bad publicity for Chastain,

486
00:20:33,265 --> 00:20:37,134
so... I would ask
you to just, please,

487
00:20:37,202 --> 00:20:39,870
tread lightly?

488
00:20:46,896 --> 00:20:49,647
Oh, you've got to be kidding me.

489
00:20:51,751 --> 00:20:53,251
Everything okay?

490
00:20:53,319 --> 00:20:54,964
Your baseball player
just sent me a picture

491
00:20:54,988 --> 00:20:57,988
of a swollen appendage
that is definitely not his leg.

492
00:20:58,041 --> 00:21:00,591
- Okay, thanks. Yeah, I got it.
- I mean...

493
00:21:00,660 --> 00:21:02,354
Thank you.

494
00:21:02,378 --> 00:21:03,822
I'm gonna talk to
Bobby. He can't do that.

495
00:21:03,846 --> 00:21:05,145
No, don't. I can handle it.

496
00:21:05,214 --> 00:21:06,291
It's not the first time
this has happened.

497
00:21:06,315 --> 00:21:08,232
Jude send one too?

498
00:21:11,554 --> 00:21:13,065
- Very funny.
- All joking aside,

499
00:21:13,089 --> 00:21:14,688
I'm talking to Bobby Singer.

500
00:21:14,757 --> 00:21:18,592
Conrad, I'm serious. I don't
want you going up there.

501
00:21:18,660 --> 00:21:20,578
And, for the record,

502
00:21:20,647 --> 00:21:22,947
Jude and I are just
friends, unlike you and Noni.

503
00:21:24,466 --> 00:21:25,599
Hey.

504
00:21:25,668 --> 00:21:26,733
Yeah, okay. Fine.

505
00:21:26,819 --> 00:21:29,036
Everything all right?

506
00:21:29,122 --> 00:21:31,182
I need a surgeon to do
the Darryl Phillips's biopsy.

